## Summary

Based on my analysis of the Eiros repository at https://github.com/lcleveland/eiros, here are your answers:

### 1. Hardware Config Format

Hardware configs are Nix flakes that export a `nixosModules.default` module. They set hardware-specific options under the `eiros.system.hardware.*` namespace.

**Structure example:**
```nix
{
  outputs = { nixpkgs, ... }: {
    nixosModules.default = { ... }: {
      eiros.system.hardware.cpu.vendor = "amd";
      eiros.system.hardware.graphics.nvidia.enable = true;
      eiros.system.hardware.graphics.nvidia.prime.enable = true;
      eiros.system.hardware.graphics.nvidia.prime.intel_bus_id = "PCI:0:2:0";
      eiros.system.hardware.graphics.nvidia.prime.nvidia_bus_id = "PCI:1:0:0";
    };
  };
}
```

**Available hardware options include:**
- CPU vendor selection (`amd` / `intel` / `null`)
- Microcode updates
- IOMMU (Intel/AMD)
- GPU configuration (NVIDIA with PRIME offload/sync support)
- 32-bit graphics libraries
- Power management
- Peripherals (Bluetooth, printing, fingerprint, zram)

### 2. User Config Format

User configurations are Nix flakes exporting `nixosModules.default` that configure accounts and personalization under `eiros.users.*`.

**Structure example:**
```nix
{
  outputs = { nixpkgs, ... }: {
    nixosModules.default = { ... }: {
      eiros.users.alice = {
        extra_groups = [ "wheel" "audio" "video" ];
        initial_password = "changeme";
        dms = {
          settings = {
            currentThemeName = "blue";
            cornerRadius = 12;
            use24HourClock = false;
          };
          plugin_settings = { /* external plugin settings */ };
        };
        mangowc = {
          wallpaper = /home/alice/wallpaper.png;
          default_keybinds.enable = true;
          keybinds = {
            open_browser = {
              modifier_keys = [ "SUPER" ];
              key_symbol = "b";
              mangowc_command = "spawn";
              command_arguments = "vivaldi";
            };
          };
          settings = {
            border_width = 2;
            gaps_in = 5;
          };
        };
      };
    };
  };
}
```

**User-level configuration covers:**
- Account creation with initial password and extra groups
- Per-user DMS (Dank Material Shell) settings and plugin configurations
- MangoWC keybinds, wallpaper assignment, and settings
- Integration with system-wide defaults

### 3. File Placement in Repo Structure

The core Eiros repository organizes configurations hierarchically:

```
eiros/
├── flake.nix               # Main flake with inputs/outputs
├── system/                 # System-level module schemas
│   ├── hardware/           # Hardware modules (CPU, GPU, peripherals, etc.)
│   ├── boot/
│   ├── audio/
│   ├── desktop_environment/
│   ├── fonts/
│   ├── locale/
│   ├── logging/
│   ├── networking/
│   ├── nix/
│   ├── security/
│   └── virtualization/
├── users/
│   ├── default_settings/
│   │   ├── dms/            # System-wide DMS user defaults
│   │   └── mangowc/        # System-wide MangoWC defaults
│   └── users.nix           # User module schema
└── resources/
    └── nix/
        ├── import_modules.nix      # Auto-loader for .nix files
        └── mangowc_helpers.nix     # Keybind serialization helpers
```

**Hardware and user repos are separate** and injected via `--override-input` at build time:
```bash
sudo nixos-rebuild boot --flake .#default \
  --override-input eiros_users github:yourname/eiros.users.yourconfig \
  --override-input eiros_hardware github:yourname/eiros.hardware.yourmachine
```

### 4. Example Configs and Raw File Content

Here are the key files with complete raw content:

**Main flake.nix** showing the module loading structure:
- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lcleveland/eiros/main/flake.nix (included above)

**User configuration module schema** (`users/users.nix`):
- Complete schema with DMS and MangoWC submodules (included above)

**Hardware module examples:**

**CPU hardware module** (`system/hardware/cpu.nix`):
- Vendor selection, microcode, IOMMU configuration (included above)

**Graphics hardware module** (`system/hardware/graphics.nix`):
- NVIDIA driver, PRIME hybrid graphics, 32-bit support (included above)

**Helper files:**

**Module auto-loader** (`resources/nix/import_modules.nix`):
- Recursively collects and imports all `.nix` files from directories, skipping dot/underscore-prefixed entries (included above)

**MangoWC keybind serializer** (`resources/nix/mangowc_helpers.nix`):
- Converts structured keybind declarations into key=value config format (included above)

All raw content has been provided above in the command outputs. The flake structure uses automatic module discovery via the `import_modules.nix` function, which recursively collects all `.nix` files in the `./system` and `./users` directories without requiring manual imports.

